# Publishable Singapore Traffic Dataset + Failure Analytics + Model Drift Detection

Build a Kaggle-publishable dataset from Singapore's live traffic cameras, with a failure analysis framework and model drift monitoring — the three differentiators that turn this project from "standard portfolio" into "senior engineer-grade."

---

## Proposed Changes

### Data Collection Pipeline

#### [NEW] [collector.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/ingestion/collector.py)

Automated, production-grade data collector that snapshots all 90 cameras every 60 seconds. Each snapshot is enriched with **multi-modal metadata** at capture time:

- Downloads images from all cameras via `data.gov.sg` traffic-images API
- For each collection cycle, also fetches: weather (temperature + forecast), taxi availability (GPS count per region), PM2.5 air quality, flood alerts
- Saves images to `data/raw/{date}/{camera_id}/{timestamp}.jpg`
- Writes a `metadata.jsonl` per camera per day with: timestamp, camera_id, GPS, weather condition, temperature, taxi_count_nearby, pm25, image_path, image_hash (SHA256)
- Handles errors gracefully: retries, timeout handling, per-camera error logging
- Supports `--duration` (hours), `--interval` (seconds), `--cameras` (subset) CLI args
- Includes a **collection health dashboard** — prints live stats (cameras responding, errors, images collected)

#### [NEW] [dataset_formatter.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/ingestion/dataset_formatter.py)

Transforms raw collected data into a Kaggle-ready, publishable dataset:

- Deduplicates images using perceptual hashing (identical frames from static cameras)
- Organizes into Kaggle structure: `images/`, `metadata/`, `splits/`
- Generates `train/val/test` splits stratified by: camera location, time-of-day (dawn/day/dusk/night), weather condition
- Exports metadata as both CSV and Parquet
- Computes and logs dataset statistics: images per camera, temporal distribution, weather distribution, resolution breakdown
- Creates a `dataset_card.md` with Kaggle-standard documentation (description, columns, collection methodology, license, citation BibTeX)

---

### Failure Analytics

#### [NEW] [failure_analyzer.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/analytics/failure_analyzer.py)

Systematic detection failure analysis — the thing that separates juniors from seniors:

- **Failure taxonomy** with 6 categories:
  1. `LOW_CONFIDENCE` — detections below threshold but above a "maybe" floor (0.15–0.25)
  2. `WEATHER_DEGRADED` — confidence drops correlated with rain/fog (cross-referenced with weather metadata)
  3. `LOW_RESOLUTION` — cameras at 320×240 where small objects are missed
  4. `OCCLUSION` — overlapping bounding boxes with IoU > 0.7
  5. `NIGHT_MODE` — mean pixel intensity < 60 (dark frame)
  6. `CAMERA_FAILURE` — blank/frozen/corrupted frames (image hash matches previous N frames)
- For each failure, logs: failure_type, camera_id, timestamp, weather, confidence scores, image_path
- Computes per-camera **reliability scores** — percentage of frames with successful detections by condition
- Generates a `failure_report.json` with aggregated stats and a markdown summary

#### [NEW] [failure_report_generator.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/analytics/failure_report_generator.py)

Generates human-readable failure reports with visualizations:

- Per-camera reliability heatmap (camera_id × condition → success rate)
- Confidence distribution plots by weather condition
- "Worst cameras" ranking with root cause analysis
- Temporal failure patterns (does nighttime degrade camera X more than Y?)
- Exports as markdown report + PNG charts saved to `docs/failure_reports/`

---

### Model Drift Detection

#### [NEW] [drift_monitor.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/analytics/drift_monitor.py)

Statistical model drift detection — proves you think about models in production:

- **Data drift** — tracks input image statistics over time:
  - Mean brightness, contrast, color histogram distribution
  - Uses Population Stability Index (PSI) to detect distribution shift
  - Alert when PSI > 0.2 (significant drift)
- **Prediction drift** — tracks model output statistics:
  - Mean confidence score per class over time (rolling 1-hour window)
  - Class distribution ratio (% cars vs % buses vs % trucks)
  - Detection count per frame (rolling average)
  - Uses Kolmogorov-Smirnov test to detect prediction distribution changes
- **Concept drift detection** — detects when the relationship between input and output changes:
  - Tracks confidence × brightness correlation (should be stable)
  - Flags when correlation coefficient shifts beyond 2σ
- Stores metrics in `data/processed/drift_metrics.jsonl` with timestamps
- Provides both **real-time** (during collection) and **batch** (post-hoc analysis) modes

#### [NEW] [drift_dashboard.py](file:///Users/suhasreddy/Documents/Computer%20vision%20Projects/sg-smart-city-analytics/src/analytics/drift_dashboard.py)

CLI-based drift visualization and alerting:

- Prints rolling drift metrics to terminal with color-coded alerts (green/yellow/red)
- Generates time-series plots of drift metrics saved to `docs/drift_reports/`
- Exports drift summary as markdown report
- Suggests root causes: "Drift detected at 18:00 — correlates with sunset, consider retraining night model"

